{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FUuBAVeXz8iHsJQ163Hj2U","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→BARSZCZ\n     2→\n     3→Growing up in Warsaw, my family made barszcz for every important occasion. My mother would spend hours\n     4→tending the pot, ensuring the beets released their deep crimson color into the broth. She always said that\n     5→the key was patience—rushing the beets would result in a pale, weak broth that didn't honor the vegetable.\n     6→This recipe comes from her collection of handwritten cards, worn and stained from decades of use in the kitchen.\n     7→It's traditionally served at Christmas Eve supper, in small cups, often with tiny savory pastries floating inside.\n     8→\n     9→Ingredients:\n    10→- 1 kg fresh beets, peeled and cut into chunks\n    11→- 2 liters beef or vegetable stock\n    12→- 1 large onion, quartered\n    13→- 3 cloves garlic, smashed\n    14→- 1 bay leaf\n    15→- 3 whole cloves\n    16→- 3-4 tablespoons red wine vinegar\n    17→- 1 tablespoon sugar\n    18→- Salt and pepper to taste\n    19→- Fresh dill for garnish\n    20→\n    21→Instructions:\n    22→1. Place beets, onion, garlic, bay leaf, and cloves in large pot with stock.\n    23→2. Bring to boil, then reduce heat and simmer gently for 60 minutes.\n    24→3. Strain broth through fine sieve, pressing gently on vegetables.\n    25→4. Return to pot and season with vinegar, sugar, salt, and pepper.\n    26→5. Heat through and serve in small cups.\n    27→6. Garnish with fresh dill.\n    28→\n    29→Traditionally served with uszka (small mushroom dumplings).\n    30→Serves 6-8 as a starter course.\n    31→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01SD8AA9LDu7w4NHpurCkETj","session_id":"fc97eaa2-7481-42f4-b7bf-89f7efc643c7","uuid":"9d274cc3-14fc-4b23-a595-f16d880ac9c1"}
